@NODE WarnWin "Warning"
Volume works patching the BeginIO vector of audio.device.
If you launch other programs that patches this vector after Volume, you MUST quit these
programs in the OPPOSITE order you launched them, otherwise you will get strange behaviour
from the system the next time some application tries to use the audio.device (gurus...)

This window just warn you every time you try to quit Volume.

If you want you coud disable Volume (selecting disabled from option menu) and iconify it
instead to quit.
@ENDNODE

@NODE InterWin "Interrupt"
In this window you can adjust interrupt duration and priority.

Since the variation of the volume is not immediate, you could wish to force it for the time
needed to get stable.
This is achieved changing directly the volume by writing into Paula's registers.
In some case it could not be enough to set these registers once, since the aplication or
the OS could change the volume again. To avoid this you could force the volume for some time
(Interrupt length) at the desired level using interrupts (Vertical Blank)

If you set Interrupt length to 0, registers will be changed only every time you move the
Audio Knob.

You can disable this deselecting the "hit the hardware" menu option.
@ENDNODE

@NODE Menu "Menu"
Below there is a short description of program's menu:

Project
  |-About               Not much to say here...
  |-Quit

Options
  |- Mute		Set the volume to zero
  |- Enabled		Disable completely Volume
  |- Audio Filter	Turn on/off the audio filter (LED)
  |- Hit the Hardware	Turn on/off the hardware direct writing/interrupts
  |-Set Int Length	Change interrupt length and priority
  |-Mui Settings	Show MUI Prefs
  |-Load Options	Load program options	
  |-Save Options	Save program options

@ENDNODE
